[normal]Hillhouse Greening the Gap[bold] (2010)[bold]Kirklees Council was successful in securing £500,000 from DECC’s Low Carbon Communities Challenge Fund
[normal] (LCCC)
[normal].
[normal] 
[normal]53 private sector houses and 4 community cen
[normal]tres in the Hillhouse area of Huddersfield had solar PV installed for free, plus other energy saving measures to improve the energy efficiency of the properties.
[normal] 
[normal]Income generated from the Feed in Tariff is being invested in the community.
[normal] To date this inco
[normal]me amounts to £58k.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]1.5.4[bold]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Energy [bold]E[bold]fficiency in Kirklees Council homes[bold] (ongoing)[bold]Kirklees Council owns ~23,000 
[normal]domestic 
[normal]properties which are managed by Kirklees Neighbourhood Housing.  The council and KNH have made significant investment in energy efficiency measures through ‘Decent Homes’ budgets and targeted energy budgets. Measures include gas boiler replacements, loft i
[normal]nsulation top ups, external wall insulation, ground source heat pumps, solar thermal hot water, solar photo voltaic and 
[normal]a 
[normal]biomass boiler. 
[normal]This investment has dramatically improved the energy efficiency of our homes, increased the average SAP rating to 72.4
[normal], reduced our carbon emissions by 23% since 2005, helped tackle fuel poverty and created local jobs and a skilled supply chain.  
[normal]&#xa0;
