[normal]3.2.3[bold]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Work [bold]to reduce carbon emissions across the[bold] Council [bold](£350k)[bold]This programme will deliver a 
[normal]range of 
[normal]energy/carbon reduction projects to reduce the Council’s energy costs and carbon emissions, and help us meet our 40% carbon reduction target by
[normal] 2020. 
[normal]These include continued investment in LED traffic lights, upgrading car park lighting and energy efficiency measures 
[normal]within council
[normal] buildings.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]4.1
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]In Kirklees, the last decade has seen a number of changes in the way the authority addresses climate change issues and communicates with the public. Initially, resources were focussed on 
[normal]raising awareness of[bold] 
[normal]climate change[bold] 
[normal]through the Council’s ‘Green Ambi
[normal]tion’ environmental 
[normal]programme, 
[normal]and explaining the scientific argument to engage people in the broader consequence of rising temperatures and what they could do at an individual level. This was in line with national media and communicating the findings from
[normal] key research such as the Stern Report. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]4.2
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]As time progressed, and council priorities 
[normal]evolved
[normal], messages which were originally about ‘tackling climate change’ became focussed on 
[normal]reducing carbon emissions[bold]. Generally speaking, the message that climate change i
[normal]s real and happening
[normal] is to an extent 
[normal]understood and accepted, and the focus moved to reducing the key cause of climate change – carbon emissions. This mirrored local authority data collection requirements such as those set out in Local Area Agreements and 
[normal]National Indicators (185 and 186). 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]4.3
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]M
[normal]ost recently, 
[normal]during
[normal] the economic downturn, communication with the public on matters concerning climate change 
[normal]has
[normal] 
[normal]centred on
[normal] 
[normal]finance[bold], fuel poverty[bold],[bold] related health issues, [bold]and job creation[bold]. 
[normal]For example, using less ener
[normal]gy in the home has been promoted as a means of mitigating the impact of income reduction from other areas such as the Welfare Reform.
[normal] 
[normal]With dramatic reductions in
[normal] council resources to support this agenda
[normal] (both in staffing levels and available investment fun
[normal]ding), p
[normal]rojects are progressed
[normal] where inward investment is generated
[normal] reducing pressure on council capital and ensuring best value for money is achieved.  
[normal] 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]4.4
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]The Council’s current 
[normal]projects
[normal] 
[normal]aimed at 
[normal]the public are 
[normal]the 
[normal]Kirklees Energy Saver
[normal] Scheme
[normal] and a recent
[normal] collective energy switch. Both schemes are aimed at supporting the residents of Kirklees to 
[normal]reduce their home energy bills[bold] and meet the Council’s key objectives of 
[normal]reducing fuel poverty and providing affordable warmth[bold]. They have both been 
[normal]communicated 
[normal]effectively via the following routes:
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]4.5
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Learning from projects has demonstrated that people have been motivated to participate in schemes for a variety of reasons. 
[normal]Financial benefits alone are in many cases unlikely to drive behaviour change; we have seen that the impact of tackling areas street by street is incredibly powerful in stimulating uptake via word of mouth and seeing neighbours take up an offer. Additional
[normal]ly, taking a scheme door to door increases uptake due to the trust in the Council brand and reassurance that contractors have been through a robust selection process.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]4.6
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]A recent development while delivering work via the Kirklees Energy Saver Scheme has been
[normal] a sudden drop in ECO funding by the energy supplier for external wall insulation. This has led to difficult communication with affected Kirklees residents, and demonstrates the challenge Councils face in maintaining trust while being vulnerable to externa
[normal]l market influences.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]5.1
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Kirklees has evidenced its extensive track record of delivering home energy efficiency projects across the district. The success of each project has involved key partners – with functions ranging from the provision of funding, to installation of physical m
[normal]easures. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]5.2
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Going forward, the council is a committed partner in the Leeds City Region and associated ‘City Deal’ and recognises that this is an effective way to engage and co-operate with our partner authorities and private sector
[normal] for the benefit of reside
[normal]nts
[normal].
[normal]&#xa0;
