[normal]6.2
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Local authorities have a lot of learning to share regarding how best to 
[normal]engage with the public
[normal] on climate change and the local and practical problems and successes of delivery
[normal].
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]6.3
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]The financial and health impacts of climate change are 
[normal]among 
[normal]the key motivators for the public to change their behaviour 
[normal]and live a greener lifestyle
[normal].
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]6.4
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Collaborative working and larger scale projects 
[normal]with other Local Authorities 
[normal]have attractive economies of scale, especially in the current climate of diminishing resources.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]6.5
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]In contrast, local authority work on 
[normal]the 
[normal]climate change 
[normal]agenda 
[normal]is at risk in vie
[normal]w of the current 
[normal](and ongoing) 
[normal]budget
[normal]ary
[normal] 
[normal]constraints
[normal], and the unreliable and unstable utility ECO funding situation.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]6.6
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Behaviour change activities are extremely resource intensive – where possible, local authorities should be enabled to continue improving h
[normal]ome energy efficiency 
[normal]with physical measures 
[normal]to reduce domestic carbon emissions.
